  "experiments_summary": "The paper trains a multimodal contrastive model jointly aligning SMILES strings and 3D electron density grids. The dataset comprises 855,000 molecules from PubChem (main-group elements up to Barium, ≤30 heavy atoms, zero net charge). For each molecule, 50 conformers are generated via RDKit distance geometry and MMFF94 optimization; the five lowest-energy conformers are reoptimized using MINDO3 in PySCF, and the lowest-energy conformer is selected. Electron densities are computed at the RHF/STO-3G level and projected onto 128×128×128 voxel grids. The 3D encoder is a 3DGrid-VQGAN with a learned codebook (16,384 entries, latent dimension 512), trained with L1 reconstruction, commitment, and 3D PatchGAN adversarial losses. The SMILES encoder is SMI-TED289M, a pretrained transformer with RoFormer-style rotary attention, which is fine-tuned during contrastive training. Two contrastive objectives are used: symmetric InfoNCE (CLIP-style) and sigmoid-based SigLIP loss. Training uses AdamW optimizer, batch size 128, learning rate 3×10⁻⁴, linear warmup over 1,000 steps, and 50,000 total steps on 4 NVIDIA A100 GPUs. Evaluation includes: (1) Canonical retrieval among unrotated molecules; (2) Unseen rotation retrieval, where test molecules are randomly rotated around six axis directions with angles uniformly sampled from [0°, 360°], generating five rotated variants per molecule (1,000 test molecules total), with electron densities recomputed for each rotation; (3) Structure–property clustering analysis using Davies–Bouldin index on HOMO energy-based clusters, focusing on nitrogen-containing species; (4) Linear probe property prediction on QM9 benchmark (12 regression tasks) using frozen embeddings. Baselines include unimodal 3DGrid-VQGAN, SE(3)-equivariant Pos-EGNN (trained on 1.4M snapshots from Materials Project Trajectory dataset), SMI-TED, and MoLFormer. Fine-tuned variants are trained on 1,000 molecules with five random rotations each. Metrics include Accuracy@10, Recall@10, functional group-wise recall, pose diversity, multi-pose retrieval rate, and Davies–Bouldin index."
